ce:section.ce:para:
Since both CB and CN can introduce defect energy levels, if both defects are present in the BN sheet and are close to each other, visible light may be emitted when electrons transit between the two distinct defect levels. Previous experimental [25] and theoretical studies [26,27] have shown that the C atoms in the BCN monolayer favor segregation, suggesting that CB and CN in the BN sheet favor to bond with one another. To confirm this possibility, we constructed a structural model of the C2 defect (CB and CN are bonded) as shown in Fig. 3
                        (a), and calculated its formation energy and electronic structure (see Fig. 4
                        ). The calculated formation energy of the C2 defect is about 3.9 eV lower than that of the separated CB + CN defects, supporting that CB and CN favor to bond with one another. More details about the relative stabilities of CB, CN and C2 can be found in the Supporting Information (SI). As seen from Fig. 4 and Fig. S1(a), no spin-splitting occurs in this case, while an empty and an occupied localized defect energy levels are introduced into the band gap, 0.59 eV below the CBM and 0.50 eV above the VBM, respectively. The energy difference between this two defect energy levels is 3.45 eV, corresponding to ultraviolet light wavelength, but not the visible light as observed in experiments.
